SIMPLE: excavation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Excavation
<hw>Ex`ca*va"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>excavatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>excavation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of excavating, or of making hollow, by cutting, scooping,
or digging out a part of a solid mass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cavity formed by cutting, digging, or
scooping.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A winding <xex>excavation</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Glover.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Engin.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An uncovered
cutting in the earth, in distinction from a <contr>covered
cutting</contr> or <contr>tunnel</contr>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The
material dug out in making a channel or cavity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The delivery of the <qex>excavations</qex> at a distance of 250
feet.</q> <rj><qau>E. L. Corthell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Excavator</ent>⟦br⟧
